\section{Introduction}

The manner in which investment decisions are arrived at is evolving fast as digital news and financial technology blows up. Sentiment signaling and real-time updates on the news sources aid the investors, analysts, and financial institutions in predicting the market movement and mitigating risk. However, the sheer volume and rate of news flow is not easily solved, and smarter systems are needed to extract drinkable information out of the flowing text at a very quick rate.
Earlier methods of sentiment analysis may not be able to handle rapid market dynamics or recognize the language of the financial reports and updates. Unexpected economic changes, the use of terms that are specific to the industry, and the lack of predictable news cycles require solutions that are flexible and scalable.
This paper describes a pipeline that will serve to address these issues directly. Our system uses a combined set of distributed big data architectures and sophisticated NLP to extract, score, and organize news on a live basis. The key technologies Apache Kafka, Spark, Redis and Elasticsearch are implemented in a modular architecture that is simple to scale and support new sources/models.
Sentiment detection is more accurate by using AI-based frameworks in conjunction with rule-based frameworks of classifying and ranking news. The infrastructure is designed to process efficiently and scale up, thus ingestion and search are both responsive and effective. The architecture opens up uncharted prospects of automatic exploration of financial text and preconditions the enhanced data-driven market analysis in the future.




\subsection{Motivation}

The financial markets continue to change with the current events going on in the world, and high-frequency news reporting. Timely news intelligence is indispensable to traders and analysts during decision making, with the amount and volume of publication being overwhelming and thus making it impossible to review the intelligence manually. Automated systems are desperately needed that are capable of scooping, processing, and comprehending news sentiment in a short period of time and offer reliable results with a low lag time.

\subsection{Contributions}

Here’s what this paper brings to the table:
\begin{itemize}
\item Our sentiment analysis real-time news pipeline consists of the combination of big data technology (Kafka, Spark) and really fast databases (such as Redis) and state-of-the-art NLP algorithms
\item Our system blends manual keyword detection with ma- chine learning models, giving more accurate, adaptable classification across different news streams.
\item The pipeline has a deduplication and risk scoring modules with human judgment (heuristics) and quantifiable analytics to give more usable insights.
\item Lastly, we consider our methods on live data streams, whereby we were enabled to reduce processing times, increase throughput, and provide more valuable and useful analytics.
\end{itemize}

\subsection {Novelty of the Proposed System}

The novelty of this work is the combination of the hybrid approach for sentiment classification and a scalable event-driven big data architecture. As opposed to currently existing financial sentiment systems, which are either purely based on deep learning models or batch processing pipelines, the proposed solution utilizes a combination of transformer-based natural language processing inference and Redis-based rule scoring in a low-latency streaming pipeline. This hybrid approach provides improved classification accuracy as well as computational efficiency and enables the ability to perform financial news analytics on resource-constrained infrastructure in real-time.


\section{Literature Survey}

\subsection {Big Data Frameworks for Financial Data Processing}

The rapid growth of financial news and digital media has engendered the need for scalable data processing systems that could handle high volume of high velocity data streams. Distributed computing frameworks like Apache Spark have seen a widespread implementation for large-scale data analytics, given the ability to efficiently handle large datasets in batch and streaming analytics applications. Zaharia et al. \cite{zaharia2016apache} introduced Apache Spark, a unified processing engine for handling big data and processing by distributing the computation on clusters. In addition, the importance for data management scalable platforms like NoSQL databases to store and query the huge amount of semi-structured data produced in the cloud environments has been highlighted by Grolinger et al. \cite{grolinger2014big}.
Several studies have been applied on big data frameworks to financial news analytics. Prasad and Kumar. \cite{} created a sentiment-aware analytics framework using Apache Spark Streaming for processing big scale news data. Jain and Wu \cite{scalable2019} proposed the use of Apache Spark and Elasticsearch in a scalable architecture for efficient indexing and querying the financial news streams. Similarly, Chawla and Soni \cite{bigdatastream2020} explored the big data stream analytics for real-time stock market prediction. Gupta and Bansal \cite{finmarket2021} further build on this body of work and combined financial news sentiment with machine learning models to predict market movements using distributed big data platforms. These studies show the effectiveness of big data infrastructures in managing large-scale financial text analytics.

\subsection {Machine Learning Approaches for Financial Sentiment Analysis}
Traditional machine learning algorithms have been extensively used for the purpose of sentiment wise analysis of financial text data. Methods such as logistic regression, support vector machines (SVM) and ensemble learning methods make use of textual features (e.g., n-grams, lexical sentiment scores, part of speech tags) to classify the polarity of financial news articles. While these approaches deliver interpretations and have relatively low computational complexion, they struggle to capture contextual relationships and semantic meaning in complex financial narratives.
In order to overcome these limitations, neural network-based techniques have been investigated by researchers. Mir and Sethi \cite{mir2025joint} introduced a joint topic--emotion modeling framework to extract thematic topics as well as the emotional sentiment from financial documents. Oka and Ritter \cite{hybrid2024} proposed a hybrid neural network architecture of topic extraction and attention mechanism for improving the accuracy of sentiment classification in financial text. Furthermore, models for interpretability of financial events evaluation have been proposed by Isane \cite{isane2024interpretable} which emphasizes the role of explainability and transparency of financial decision support systems.

\subsection {Transformer-Based Financial Language Models}

Recent developments in natural language processing have brought about a task of transformer-based architectures that greatly enhance the performance of the task of sentiment classification. Transformer models make use of self-attention mechanisms to pick up contextual relationships between words in large textual data. Kim and Wang \cite{stockbert2023} created StockBERT, a domain-specific transformer model that is fine-tuned for financial sentiment analysis. Similarly, Banerjee and Gupta \cite{finllama2024} came up with FinLLaMA, a financial domain large language model for algorithmic trading use cases and sentiment prediction.
In addition to deep learning models, a number of practical implementations of large-scale sentiments analysis pipeline have been developed. For example, event-driven financial news impact prediction frameworks based on complex event processing and distributed architectures have also been proposed \cite{cep2023framework} . Domain-specific pretrained models like FinSoSent have also shown good performance in financial sentiment detection by exploiting domain-specific financial corpora \cite{finsosent2024}. Patel and Roy \cite{nlpml2024} further stressed on the use of natural language processing techniques and machine learning frameworks to be used for real-time financial sentiment analytics.

\subsection {Comparison with Existing Research and Research Gap}
Although there has been substantial progress in financial sentiment analysis through machine learning, deep learning and big data technologies, there are still a few challenges. A lot of the existing studies are either focused on predictive modeling or batch-based sentiment analysis and not entirely integrated real-time analytics pipeline. Additionally, deep learning models can be computationally expensive, which can cause latency issues in real-time streaming systems. Furthermore, most of the approaches are based only on black-box machine learning models, which diminishes interpretability and transparency in the process of financial decision making.

In contrast, a scalable real-time financial news sentiment analysis pipeline based on distributed streaming technologies and hybrid sentiment classification is proposed in this paper. The architecture includes a combination of Apache Kafka and Apache Spark for the real-time data ingestion and processing feature and the use of a hybrid classification mechanism that includes a combination of transformer-based NLP models along with Redis-based keyword scoring. This hybrid approach not only helps to improve the interpretability and computational efficiency but it also helps in low-latency processing of financial news streams. Additionally, the deployment of containerized microservices and the usage of monitoring tools provide the flexibility of deploying and scaling the system, making the proposed architecture suitable for real-time financial analytics applications.




\section{Methodology}


\subsection{System Overview and Architecture}

The system is designed in a modular microservices pipeline format that is optimized for real-time financial news analytics. The entire workflow from beginning to end can be visualized in Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture}.



\begin{itemize}
    \item The pipeline begins with the \textit{Ingestion Service}, which retrieves raw news articles from the MarketAux API. 
    This service performs data cleansing, duplicate removal, and an initial classification using local machine learning and NLP models, 
    with scoring supported by Redis-based keyword matching.

    \item A \textit{Kafka streaming layer} acts as an intermediate buffer between ingestion and processing stages, ensuring scalable 
    and fault-tolerant message delivery. Raw and partially enriched data are published to distinct Kafka topics to support multiple 
    downstream consumers.
    
\item The \textit{Data Enrichment Service} processes Kafka streams using Apache Spark, 
computing risk scores, normalized confidence values, and impact metrics based on 
pre-computed sentiment and category classifications. Enriched data are stored 
in Elasticsearch.

    \item \textit{Elasticsearch} forms the core backend storage layer of the system, enabling high-speed indexing, filtering, 
    and aggregation to support real-time dashboard visualizations.

    \item A \textit{Node.js} backend exposes RESTful APIs that provide sentiment trends, category distributions, and 
    ticker-specific analytics. These APIs are consumed by a \textit{React/Vite} frontend, which renders interactive 
    visualizations using the Recharts library.

    \item \textit{Prometheus} is employed for collecting system-level metrics, while \textit{Grafana} provides real-time 
    monitoring dashboards. All services are orchestrated using \textit{Docker Compose} to ensure consistency in deployment 
    and operational management.
\end{itemize}

