\section{Experiments and Results}

Our pipeline integrates both backend and frontend technologies for providing real-time financial news analytics that is seamlessly scalable and makes it easy for our users to monitor the health of the system as they interact with results.



\subsection{Backend and Service Layer}

For the backend, we are using Node.js for providing a fast API so that analytics operations can happen smoothly. The API communicates directly with the Elasticsearch, which means that the users and dashboards will find up-to-date news, sentiment, and trend data - whether they want to search for a particular article or receive information on movement over a specific time window. The backend is also capable to update records and add new analysis results as required.
In the backend, we use Python microservices to handle the ingestion of raw news, the transformation of these raw news, and their output to the enriched data into Elasticsearch. Kafka takes care of all messaging, including reliable updates of events with event-driven messaging and allows different parts of the system to work in harmony. With the availability of querying capabilities within Elastic- search, the Node. js layer can provide deep filtering, trend charts and category breakdowns directly to your dashboard or app.
To ensure that everything remains robust, each of the major components has endpoints for system health and metrics, which means that tools such as Prometheus and Grafana can always monitor performance. All backend services are organized using the Docker Compose, which makes it easy to deploy and scale them in a repeatable manner.



\subsection{Experimental Design and Architecture Choices}

While building and testing the pipeline, the main goal was to keep deployment simple and the use of resources low. Instead of using complex server configurations or cloud filesystems, we deployed all the core components (Kafka, Redis, and Elasticsearch) inside Docker containers. \cite{kafka} - \cite{elasticsearch}. This approach had the benefit of enabling each service to run in its own isolated environment and made starting/stopping/updating components much easier.
Surprisingly, the entire pipeline could be made to run smoothly on a very standard hardware including the ones with just 8GB of RAM. This indicates that now powerful, multi-service analytics setups are possible without having to rely on specialized or expensive cloud resources. By containerizing all of it, it was quick and easy to repeat and make changes to the experiments, which was helpful when benchmarking different AI models to detect sentiment and measuring the speed and efficiency of the overall architecture.


\subsection{Machine Learning Model Integration}

The system is designed to plug in a number of machine learning models as modular Python components, all exposed via a simple prediction endpoint respectively. For the current version, models like DistilBART, FinBERT and DeepSeek are used to process in-coming articles, generate sentiment score summaries, assign sentiment scores and classify news into categories like earnings and quarterly results, mergers and acquisitions, regulatory developments, market trends, ESG and macro-geopolitical events. The outputs from the raw model are then combined with rule-based logic and normalized into a consistent form of confidence messages and then enriched with the final category labels. All enriched records are stored in Elasticsearch to give the ability for users to make flexible, multi-key queries (by ticker, category, time window or sentiment) and explore results in real time.


\subsection{Frontend and Analytical Visualization}

The dashboard interface is built using React and Vite which means that it's fast, responsive and feels modern to use. News articles are displayed in an organized way in cards, where some of the most relevant information is highlighted, such as the title, the sentiment, the ticker, and the category. Each company or ticker symbol has its own real-time chart, which displays the changes in the categories of sentiment and news as well as the interactions between them over time, using the Recharts library.
Users receive easy-to-use filters to narrow down based on date, sentiment score, risk or company along with pre-built tools to group and aggregate the impact of news on sectors or tickers. Figure 3 indicates what this dashboard looks like in practice. You can even connect Prometheus and Grafana with the frontend in order to monitor things like latency, throughput along with the analytics. For a more in-depth look at how the market as a whole feels, and how the various categories are changing, see Figure~\ref{fig:graphs}.

